                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">#1: Remove all this damage table nonsense.  
<br />

<br />
#2: Ensure that all mobs hereforward dual wield naturally, so handing them weapons just makes them proc a little.
<br />

<br />
#3: Add a 100% speed buff on charm fade.  This buff will overwrite snare and root and will last 30 seconds or so.
<br />

<br />
#4: (Optional) Add a %1 slow component to charm to prevent hasting pets.
<br />

<br />
What this does:
<br />

<br />
#1: ensures that mob DPS is in line with Mobs, not hasted, Dual Wielding mobs.
<br />

<br />
#2: Forces the enchanter to deal, in a very personal and up close fashion, with their ex-pet when it breaks charm.   No snaring or rooting it to save them.  Sure, you can stun it if you're fast enough, but you'll have to be damn fast, similarly, you could probably taunt it off or something, but you can't park it or kite it, so even if someone else -does- grab aggro, they need to be able to mitigate that DPS. 
<br />

<br />
In essence, these changes make it so that the enchanter can take a pet, and get appropriately improved DPS, at the cost of having to DEAL with that DPS when charm wears off.  The risk is inherently equivalent to the reward.  No watching the snared pet hobble feebly closer as charm is refreshed.  
<br />

<br />
Charm has never been the problem.  SNARE is the real root of the issue here, as it has always been.  (Runspeed buffs/debuffs are the oldest problem in EQ.)
<br />

<br />
If the enchanter and his group can handle a charmed pet in these circumstances, they deserve the extra DPS (Which will be less extreme than in the past, to boot.).
<br />

<br />
As demonstrated by the current "fix" any other solution doesn't really treat the problem.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
